==English==
[[File:Typical yakitori 001.jpg|thumb|A dish of '''yakitori''']]
===Etymology===
Borrowed from {{bor|en|ja|焼き鳥}} ({{m|ja|やきとり}}), from {{m|ja|焼き|tr=yaki|t=grilled, toasted}} + {{m|ja|鳥|tr=tori|t=bird}}.
===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/jækɪˈtɔəɹi/}}
** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-yakitori.wav|Audio (Berkshire)}}
===Noun===
{{en-noun|~|yakitori|s}}
# A Japanese [[shish kebab]]-type dish made with small pieces of chicken or other ingredients cooked on skewers, often marinated in soy sauce or seasoned with salt.
#* {{RQ:Gibson Neuromancer|page=10|passage=Friday night on Ninsei. He passed '''yakitori''' stands and massage parlors, a franchised coffee shop called Beautiful Girl, the electronic thunder of an arcade.}}
#* '''2006''', Thomas Pynchon, ''Against the Day'', Vintage 2007, p. 851:
#*: We should have the bazaars full of '''yakitori''' pitches and geishas in bamboo cages.
===See also===
* {{l|en|kushiyaki}}
